====Modern====

After [[World War I]], [[avant-garde]] photographers such as [[Brassaï]], [[Man Ray]], [[Hans Bellmer]], [[André Kertész]] and [[Bill Brandt]] became more experimental in their portrayal of nudity, using reflective distortions and printing techniques to create abstractions or depicting real life rather than classical allusions. [[Alfred Stieglitz]]'s photos of [[Georgia O'Keeffe]] are examples of some of the earliest nudes presented in an intimate and personal style rather than with dispassionate idealization. [[Edward Weston]],<ref>Conger</ref> [[Imogen Cunningham]],<ref>Cunningham</ref> [[Ruth Bernhard]], [[Harry Callahan (photographer)|Harry Callahan]], [[Emmet Gowin]] and [[Edward Steichen]] continued this trend. Weston evolved a particularly American aesthetic, using a [[large format]] camera to capture images of nature and landscapes as well as nudes, establishing photography as a fine arts medium. In 1937 Weston became the first photographer to be awarded a John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Fellowship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ccp.uair.arizona.edu/item/234|title=Edward Weston Photographs|publisher=Center for Creative Photography at the University of Arizona Libraries|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100725011346/http://ccp.uair.arizona.edu/item/234|archivedate=2010-07-25|df=}}</ref> For a famous example of Weston's work see: [[Charis Wilson]]. Many fine art photographers have a variety of subjects in their work, the nude being one. [[Diane Arbus]] was attracted to unusual people in unusual settings, including a nudist camp. [[Lee Friedlander]] had more conventional subjects, one being [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] as a young model.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/Music/02/12/madonna.photo.auction/index.html?iref=mpstoryview |title=Nude photo of Madonna goes for $37,500 |date=February 12, 2009 |publisher=CNN}}</ref>

====Contemporary====
The distinction between fine art and glamour is often one of marketing, with fine art being sold through galleries or dealers in limited editions signed by the artist, and glamour photos being distributed through mass media. For some, the difference is in the gaze of the model; glamour models look into the camera, while art models do not.<ref>{{Citation| author=Conrad,Donna | publisher=PhotoVision| title = A Conversation with Ruth Bernhard|volume=1|issue=3| year = 2000 | url = http://www.photovisionmagazine.com/articles/bernhard.interview.html}}</ref> Glamour and fashion photographers have aspired to fine art status in some of their work. One such photographer was [[Irving Penn]], who progressed from ''Vogue'' magazine to photographing fashion models such as [[Kate Moss]] nude. [[Richard Avedon]], [[Helmut Newton]] and [[Annie Leibovitz]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/exhibitions/annie_leibovitz/|title=Exhibitions: Annie Leibovitz: A Photographer's Life, 1990–2005|publisher=The Brooklyn Museum|accessdate=10 November 2012}}</ref> have followed a similar path with portraits of the famous, many of them nude.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2006/feb/08/photography.art|title=Not naked but nude|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=12 November 2012|location=London|first=Jonathan|last=Jones|date=8 February 2006}}</ref> or partially clothed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/features/2008/06/miley200806|title=Miley Knows Best|publisher=Vanity Fair|year=2008|accessdate=11 November 2012}}</ref> In the post-modern era, where fame is often the subject of fine art,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2012/feb/22/andy-warhol-legacy-lives-on|title=Andy Warhol's legacy lives on in the factory of fame|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=1 November 2012|location=London|first=Alex|last=Needham|date=22 February 2012}}</ref> Avedon's photo of [[Nastassja Kinski]] with a python, and Leibovitz's magazine covers of [[More Demi Moore|Demi Moore pregnant]] and in [[Demi's Birthday Suit|body paint]] have become iconic. The work of [[Joyce Tenneson]] has gone the other way, from fine art with a unique, soft-focus style showing women at all stages of life to portraiture of famous people and fashion photography.

Although nude photographers have largely worked within established forms that show bodies as sculptural abstractions, some, such as [[Robert Mapplethorpe]], have created works that deliberately blur the boundaries between [[Erotic photography|erotica]] and art.

Several photographers have become controversial because of their nude photographs of underage subjects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reason.com/archives/1998/05/01/photo-flap|title=Photo Flap|publisher=Reason|year=1998|accessdate=11 November 2012}}</ref> [[David Hamilton (photographer)|David Hamilton]] often used erotic themes.<ref>Hamilton</ref><ref>Sturges, 1991 & 1994</ref> [[Sally Mann]] was raised in rural Virginia, in a locale where [[Nude swimming|skinny-dipping]] in a river was common, so many of her most famous photographs are of her own children swimming in the nude.<ref>Mann & Price</ref> Less well-known photographers have been charged as criminals for photos of their own children.<ref>Powell</ref>

[[Body image]] has become a topic explored by many photographers working with models whose bodies do not conform to conventional prejudices about beauty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rmichelson.com/artist_pages/nimoy/pages/MaxBeaut.htm|title=Leonard Nimoy: The Full Body Project|publisher=R.Michelson Galleries|accessdate=11 November 2012}}</ref>
